feedback: This was so unfortunate. This was so close to being good! The film was truly so close to being powerful and good. It could have centred those who have been wrongfully convicted. It could have given them a platform to speak their experiences and words for others to hear, it could have been so much. Instead, it was the culmination of white male privilege, of being able to use university resources to further an artistic pursuit, while tacking on a social cause to garner funding. See the bit about the canjo, for example. It was all fun and games, and as soon as they heard about a real story of an incarcerated individual with one, it was all of a sudden cause to put it in their performance. It's derivative, exploitative and panders to privileged people who want to feel as though they're doing something. What is your little song and dance doing for elementary school students? What is your performance doing when sitting in front of a room of Black high school students? Do we think that Black youth in America are unaware of the flaws in the justice system? That they need to be told by two privileged white men about the risks of wrongful imprisonment? When reading out the names and hitting rocks with hammers, when ripping up the numbers, why were the vast majority of the names men? What about the women who are wrongfully convicted? I heard Anna's name, but no other woman. This film was so close to being meaningful for anyone other than the two musicians, and yet, here we are. What a shame.

feedback:
I am someone who has worked as an Amnesty International fundraiser, where I regularly discussed prisoners of conscience. I am also a musician who plays guitar and drums. But even still, this documentary was extremely uninteresting to me. Too much time was spent introducing it (first at a theatre, and then again in the classroom), and when we did finally hear more from the woman who was jailed despite being innocent, we barely learned anything about her story. Instead, the majority of the video was about the two musicians and their story, which is far less interesting. I think a good 45 minutes could have been cut from the video and it would have gotten the same points across. Watching them rehearse was not interesting at all. Seeing the end performances was cool and showed their talent, but the rehearsals just felt like random noise. 

There were also several points I thought would be perfect ends to the video (after the first "ripping" up the paper performance, and then again after the hammer performance.) But the video just kept going, it really felt like it would never end.

I am sorry for being so critical, but I am only this critical because the video combines two things I am extremely passionate about, and I felt bored, so I can only imagine how others would feel. This is an important subject but I don't feel it's presented here in a way that would maintain people's interest.
